    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-02-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-02-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="1365"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1365">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 412.11/59.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1266.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 19, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to the matter of the American claims
                    growing out of the recent revolution I have the honor to inform the Department
                    that on February 15th I informally requested Mr. Calero, Mexican Minister for
                    Foreign Affairs, to inform me what action had been taken therein. Mr. Calero
                    stated that instructions had already been sent to the Mexican Consul at El Paso
                    to institute an investigation into the matter of the claims growing out of the
                    El Paso-Ciudad Juárez incident. He said that he had no confidence in the Mexican
                    Consul at Douglas and was making a change in the consular representation there
                    in order that the Mexican Government might have the benefit of an intelligent
                    and thorough investigation into the facts. Mr. Calero thought that this
                    contemplated change might, be brought about in two or three days. Mr. Calero
                    further said that he had referred the Alamo cases to the Minister of Justice,
                    who is understood to be arranging the method of judicial investigation.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry Lane Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
